Title: Hogeveen, J., Krug, M. K., Elliott, M. V., & Solomon, M. (2018). Insula-Retrosplenial Cortex Overconnectivity Increases Internalizing via Reduced Insight in Autism. Biological Psychiatry, (15), 1–8. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biopsych.2018.01.015
Notes: Preprocessing details in supplementary, Couldnot find coordinates, GCOR was included as nuisance variable to compensate for the motion in group contrasts. (FSIQ)>70 .  group differences in functional connectivity observed in the current study remained significant whether or not the average global correlation regressor was modeled. MNI coordinates of all the written regions are asked from authors
Medication: None - Ten participants in the ASD group were taking prescribed psychostimulants but refrained from taking medica- tions for $48 hours in advance of their MRI
Summary: Hogeveen et al. annalyzed the resting state functional connectivity between 3 important brain networks - Default mode network(DMN), Sailence networ (SN) and frontoparietal network (FPN). They took an atlas having 400 parcellations which was segmented into seven functional netwoks. The ROIx x ROI analysis was  done with the ROIs that lie in the 3 networks under study. Between group analysis yielded SN-DMN overconnectivity in ASD.

Title: Tomasi, D., & Volkow, N. D. (2017). Reduced Local and Increased Long-Range Functional Connectivity of the Thalamus in Autism Spectrum Disorder. Cerebral Cortex.
Summary: Tomasi et al. analyzed the thalamus in the combined ABIDE I and II dataset. They looked at how the long range and short range connectivity differs between ASD and TD. For long range connectivity they used the traditional FC measure and for short range they used local functional connectivity density measure. For long range connectivity difference they did the seed x voxel FC analysis to find out incereased connectivity in ASD as compared to TD between thalamus and the regions involved in social congnition such as insula, auditory, somatosensory areas etc.

Title: Olivito, G., Lupo, M., Laghi, F., Clausi, S., Baiocco, R., Cercignani, M., ... & Leggio, M. (2018). Lobular patterns of cerebellar resting‐state connectivity in adults with Autism Spectrum Disorder. European Journal of Neuroscience, 47(6), 729-735.
Summary: Olivitio et al. went ahead and analyzed both voxel morphometry as well as functional connectivity of cerebellum with the whole brain. They found volume of crux II of cerebellum to be altered in ASD. With the Crux II as seed they performed based analysis and found cerebellar-cerebrum underconnectivity with cerebellar-cerebellar overconenctivity.

Title: Hong, S. J., Valk, S. L., Di Martino, A., Milham, M. P., & Bernhardt, B. C. (2017). Multidimensional Neuroanatomical Subtyping of Autism Spectrum Disorder. Cerebral Cortex, 1-11.
Summary: Hong et al. categorised ASD subject into 3 neuroanatomical subtypes and did supervised learning for single subject prediction of ADOS scores. They got a better performance with their subtyping approach. They also did ROIxROI resting state FC analysis for subjects in each of the subtypes independently with ROIs identified using meta analysis of published studies on mentalizing and communication from Neurosynth.org. They observed underconnectivity in all the 3 subtypes as compared to TD.

Title: Wang, J., Fu, K., Chen, L., Duan, X., Guo, X., Chen, H., ... & Chen, H. (2017). Increased Gray Matter Volume and Resting-State Functional Connectivity in Somatosensory Cortex and their Relationship with Autistic Symptoms in Young Boys with Autism Spectrum Disorder. Frontiers in physiology, 8, 588.
Summary: One of the studies that utilised youngest of cohorts was by Wang et al. where they took children with age 3-7 years and used a combined method where they found the regions with altered grey matter volume in ASD using VBM and then took these regions as seeds and did a seed-voxel based FC analysis. Incleased GMV was found in left superior temporal gyrus (STG) and left postcentral gyrus (PCG) in ASD children. Taking both of these regions as seeds for FC analysis revealed altered PCG connectivity in ASD children.

Title: Shou, X. J., Xu, X. J., Zeng, X. Z., Liu, Y., Yuan, H. S., Xing, Y., ... & Han, J. S. (2017). A volumetric and functional connectivity MRI study of brain arginine-vasopressin pathways in autistic children. Neuroscience bulletin, 33(2), 130-142.
Notes:
The MNI Coordinates of the seed were not found. Paper said it was in supp material but the supp material was not available. But it was mentioned that AAL atlas was used for the seed selection So I used http://neuro.compute.dtu.dk/services/brededatabase/index_roi_tzouriomazoyer.html to get the Talaraich coordinates of the seed regions which was then converted to MNI using http://sprout022.sprout.yale.edu/mni2tal/mni2tal.html.
Children were kept in the scanner for 10-15 minutes but nowhere in the paper was mentioned the exact time.
Gender alog with age was also included as covariates
Summary: Shou et al examined the involvement of arginine-vaso- pressin (AVP) systems i.e. the brain regions that contain AVP neurons. These regions are hippocampus, amygdala and hypothalamus. They analyzed the volume as well as FC of these structures. The observations were bilaterally shrunken hypothalamus and enlarged left amygdala and left hippocampus. Further FC of left hippocampus and left amygdala revealed underconneced amygdala and supramarginal gyrus and overconned hippocamus and thalamus.

OverConnectivityName: right basal ganglia and right thalamic area (rBG/TH)

Title: Guo, X., Duan, X., Long, Z., Chen, H., Wang, Y., Zheng, J., ... & Chen, H. (2016). Decreased amygdala functional connectivity in adolescents with autism: A resting-state fMRI study. Psychiatry Research: Neuroimaging, 257, 47-56.
Notes: The supplementary sheet showed the results of analysis without GSR. But as the results were uncorrected, I didnt include those. Also, this study was restricted to regions that were significantly positively correlated with the amygdala. They didnt take into account the voxels that were negative correlated with amygdala coz of issues around GSR. Sex and FIQ was also regressed out. Though later they said that regressing out FIQ didnt have a significant effect. Analysis after scrubbing showed only overlap results and not results independently of each site, so discarded.
Summary: Another study that analyzed amygdala connectivity was by Guo et al in which they independently analyzed 2  datasets from ABIDE -  UCLA and Leuven. They calculated seed-voxel functional connectivity for the whole brain but analyzed only the voxels that were significantly positively correlated with amygdala (which they said was because using GSR in their preprocssing pipeline). The observation was large scale underconnectivity with left /right amygdala in both the datasets, some overconnectivity with right amygdala seed was also observed with UCLA datset. Along with the group differences for individual sites, they also presented the results of connectivity difference that overlapped in these two data sets.

Title: Guo, X., Duan, X., Long, Z., Chen, H., Wang, Y., Zheng, J., ... & Chen, H. (2016). Decreased amygdala functional connectivity in adolescents with autism: A resting-state fMRI study. Psychiatry Research: Neuroimaging, 257, 47-56.

Shen, M. D., Li, D. D., Keown, C. L., Lee, A., Johnson, R. T., Angkustsiri, K., ... & Nordahl, C. W. (2016). Functional connectivity of the amygdala is disrupted in preschool-aged children with autism spectrum disorder. Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry, 55(9), 817-824.
Notes:
This paper has used GSR and also analysed the data without GSR and got 'strikingly similar' results. They go on to claim that, this is because that the acquired data was very high quality (no motion) that the unexplained variance i.e. the noise was taken care by WM and CSF only.
SMA = Supplementary motor area. The amygdala seeds were manually traced in native space, not in MNI standard space, so those do not have corresponding MNI coordinates. So I have used HO atlas to get the MNI Coordinates. SImilarly for the other regions mentioned, cluster spans across multiple regions, so in addition to the peak t-val coordinate, the author has reported the volume % of the voxel for the other regions. I have ignored such regions as I have reported either the peak coordinate or COG of the cluster.  Also the authors have taken one ROI of Primary visual cortex using freesurfer that doesnot differentiate between Left and Right Hemisphere so I have broken it down to 2 ROIs and assigned the coordinates from Juliech Atlas.
Summary: In this study Shen et al analyzed amygdala in naturally sleeping preschool aged children. They observed a major underconnectivity in ASD children in FC between amygdala and areas involved in social communication and repetitive behaviours. They did a parallel FC based study using a seed in primary visual area (V1) and here as well observed underconnectivity to sensorymotor areas.

Title: Green, S. A., Hernandez, L., Bookheimer, S. Y., & Dapretto, M. (2016). Salience network connectivity in autism is related to brain and behavioral markers of sensory overresponsivity. Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry, 55(7), 618-626.
Notes: Looks like this site has their data in ABIDE as they have common TR and number of volumes i.e. 120
Summary: In this study Green et al examined the whole brain conenctivity witht the sailence network with right anterior insula as the seed. They observed only overconnectivity with of AI with primary sensory regions in ASD as compred to TD such as regions in auditory cortex and occipital cortex.

Title: Olivito, G., Clausi, S., Laghi, F., Tedesco, A. M., Baiocco, R., Mastropasqua, C., ... & Leggio, M. (2017). Resting-state functional connectivity changes between dentate nucleus and cortical social brain regions in autism spectrum disorders. The Cerebellum, 16(2), 283-292.
Notes: gender was also included as covariate of no interest, No connectivity alteration was found between right DN and the cerebral corte. The paper says the subjects were Aspergers or High functioning. I think they considered both same
Summary: The involvement of cerebellum in the etiology of ASD is well known. To shed some light on this Olivitio et al. did rsFC analysis of Dentate nucleus (cerebellum) in subjects with aspergers's syndrome. They observed decreased connectivity between left dentate nucleus and cerebral regions involved in social cognition like angular gyrus/ supramarginal gyrus and other higher order emotional processes. Further analysis of left dentate nuclues in cerebellum only reveled over connectivity in some areas which are associated with DMN.

Title: Zhou, Y., Shi, L., Cui, X., Wang, S., & Luo, X. (2016). Functional connectivity of the caudal anterior cingulate cortex is decreased in autism. PloS one, 11(3), e0151879.
Notes:
Bad volumes were included in regression model. Partial correlation was done while controlling for the effect of the other ROIs. With covariance
including age, site, FIQ, and FD. In the discussion the authors mention that the subjects can be termed as high functioning as the FIQ of autistic subjects was >= Average.(The subjects were included if they lied withing 2 standard deviations of group mean)
Summary: Anterior Cingulate Cortex, which was reported to have involvement with the intrinsic networks was analyzed in the study by Zhou et al. They analyzed the whole brain functional connectivity of five bilateral subregions of ACC which they took as seeds. They observed only left claudal ACC to be underconnected. It was underconnected with the regions mostly related to sensorimotor networks of the brain i.e. insula, postcentral gyrus, superior temporal gyrus etc.
IQ Notes: The subjects were included if they lied withing 2 standard deviations of group mean

Title: Rausch, A., Zhang, W., Haak, K. V., Mennes, M., Hermans, E. J., van Oort, E., ... & Groen, W. B. (2016). Altered functional connectivity of the amygdaloid input nuclei in adolescents and young adults with autism spectrum disorder: a resting state fMRI study. Molecular autism, 7(1), 13.
Notes: FIQ > 80 was taken as inclusion criteria. Did ICA based noise removal and the used RETROICOR to removes physiological noise. Entire Amygdala ROI was constructed by merging the 3 Amygdala subregions LB, SF, CM (given in Juliech). But as such the MNI of Entire Amygdala was not given so I took the one from HO Subcortical Atlas.
Summary: Another region that is observed to be impared in ASD individuals is amygdala. Rausch et al. analyzed the seed-voxel functional connectivity of multiple amygdaloid subregions as well as entire amygdala. They observed underconnectivity with only sensory input channels of amygdala i.e. Left Superficial (SF) nuclei and Right laterobasal (LB) nuclei with multiple brain regions indicating abnormal socio-perceptual pathways. They also observed both left and right entire amygdala seed to be underconnected with multiple regions of the brain.

Title: Burrows, C. A., Laird, A. R., & Uddin, L. Q. (2016). Functional connectivity of brain regions for self‐and other‐evaluation in children, adolescents and adults with autism. Developmental science, 19(4), 564-580.
Summary: To investigate the impairment in understanding self and others in individuals in autism, Burrows et al. studied the resting state seed to whole brain voxels FC of the regions involved in self-refrential and other-refrential processing i.e. mPFC and PCC respectivrly. They analyzed 3 seperate cohorts independently - children, adolocents and adults and found reduced FC of mPFC and PCC in children with ASD. They also observed reduced FC of just PCC in adults with ASD. But did not observe any significant group differences between adolocents with ASD and typically developing adolocents .

Title: Burrows, C. A., Laird, A. R., & Uddin, L. Q. (2016). Functional connectivity of brain regions for self‐and other‐evaluation in children, adolescents and adults with autism. Developmental science, 19(4), 564-580.

Elton, A., Di Martino, A., Hazlett, H. C., & Gao, W. (2016). Neural connectivity evidence for a categorical-dimensional hybrid model of autism spectrum disorder. Biological psychiatry, 80(2), 120-128.
Notes: Number of ASD subjects and corresponding subtypes categories doesnot add up. They combines L and R ROIs for IPS in the analysis. So I wrote it seperately in the results. The MNI coordinates of L and R were given
Summary: Elton et al in their study, analyzed the resting state FC of DMN, DAN, SN and ECN which are 4 brain neural networks in the brain. They took a seed cluster of voxels corresponding to each of the network which represented each of the network. They they created seed-voxel FC maps of the whole brain with the above chosen seeds. They observed a mix of over and under connectivity of all the seeds with the brain.

UnderConnectivityName: L superior tempporal gyrus, angular gyrus
L superior tempporal gyrus, angular gyrus

Title: Kleinhans, N. M., Reiter, M. A., Neuhaus, E., Pauley, G., Martin, N., Dager, S., & Estes, A. (2016). Subregional differences in intrinsic amygdala hyperconnectivity and hypoconnectivity in autism spectrum disorder. Autism Research, 9(7), 760-772.
OverConnectivityName: L Occipital pole, Lingual gyrus, intracalcarine
Notes: Used 3Ddespike from AFNI to removie the spikes in the data, Used MELODIC to denoide the data. ROI approach to test for connectivity differences in the right and left nucleus accumbens
Summary: Kleinhans et al. analysed amygdala at subregional level by analyzing its FC with the whole brain in a seed-voxel manner   except nucleus accumbens whcich due to being small in size was analzed in seed-roi manner. The 3 subregions were cnetromedial (CM), laterobasal(LB) and superficial (SF). The authors observed  CM and SF to be overconnected and LB to be over connected with multiple regions of the brain.

OverConnectivityName: R Occipital fusiform gyrus (lateral occipital cortex, crus I, occipital pole)
R Frontal pole (superior frontal gyrus, paracingulate gyrus)
L Lateral occipital cortex (crus I, occipital pole)
L Lateral occipital cortex, inferior division

Title: Yerys, B. E., Gordon, E. M., Abrams, D. N., Satterthwaite, T. D., Weinblatt, R., Jankowski, K. F., ... & Vaidya, C. J. (2015). Default mode network segregation and social deficits in autism spectrum disorder: Evidence from non-medicated children. NeuroImage: Clinical, 9, 223-232.
Notes: age, sex, Full-Scale IQ, and root mean squared volume-to-volume dis-placement of all voxels as covariates of no interest.
Summary: Yerys et al. analyzed the FC 6 DMN regions with the whole brain voxels and observed a mix of over and underconnectivity in ASD as compared to controls. They also used graph theoretic approaches (that is beyond the scope of this review) to demostrate the potential of some DMN regions to be considered as endophenotype for social defects.

Title: Hoffmann, F., Koehne, S., Steinbeis, N., Dziobek, I., & Singer, T. (2016). Preserved self-other distinction during empathy in autism is linked to network integrity of right supramarginal gyrus. Journal of autism and developmental disorders,46(2), 637-648.
Notes: number of sites, age and FIQ were included in the model as covariates of no interest.
Summary: Hoffman et al. worked with high functioning Autistic subjects to study 2 regions - rSMG which is involved in emotional egocentricity and rTPJ which is involved in theory of mind (TOM) and observed that ADS showed reduced resting state  functional connectivity from rTPJ to lTPJ, precuneus, PCC and MPFC. But interestingly didn't find any significant difference in the autistic and neurotypical group for rSMG seed, pointing to the intact emotion egocentrivity.

Title: Fishman, I., Datko, M., Cabrera, Y., Carper, R. A., & Müller, R. A. (2015). Reduced integration and differentiation of the imitation network in autism: A combined functional connectivity magnetic resonance imaging and diffusion‐weighted imaging study. Annals of neurology, 78(6), 958-969.
Summary: Fishman et al. did a multimodal investigation of the imitation network of the brain by using resting state fMRI and DTI. They then defined 14 ROIs comprising the imitation network using meta analysis. They performed whole brain seed-voxel FC analysis for each of the 14 seeds. Between group level analysis yielded both significant over and underconnectivity of multiple seeds in ASD. They concluded that in ASD the immitation network has increased connectivity of immitation regions with the  regions outside immitation network  but reduced connectivity within imitation network.

SeedName: Left SI/IPS5: primary somatosensory cortex/intraparietal sulcus

Title: Carper, R. A., Solders, S., Treiber, J. M., Fishman, I., & Müller, R. A. (2015). Corticospinal tract anatomy and functional connectivity of primary motor cortex in autism. Journal of the American Academy of Child & Adolescent Psychiatry, 54(10), 859-867.
Notes: Volumes = 185 -5
Summary: Carper et al. investigated both the functional and structural connectivity of theprimary motor area. For accessing functional connectivity they took left and right precentral gyrus seeds and analyzed their FC with the all the voxels of the brain. They observed majority of over connectivity with both the seeds with just left prrecentral gyrus seed showing additional underconnectivity with left middle occipital gyrus.

Title: Abbott, A. E., Nair, A., Keown, C. L., Datko, M., Jahedi, A., Fishman, I., & Müller, R. A. (2016). Patterns of atypical functional connectivity and behavioral links in autism differ between default, salience, and executive networks. Cerebral Cortex, 26(10), 4034-4045.
OverConnectivityName: L Inferior parietal lobule extending to superior parietal lobule and cuneus
Notes: 5 volumes were discarded
Summary: Abbott et al. analyzed the 4 main functional networks of human brain - default-mode (DMN), salience (SN), and left (lECN) and right executive control (rECN). Resting-state functional MRI data from75 children. They took representative seeds  for each of the functional networks and did functional connectivity analysis with the whole brain voxels. They observed mixed connectivity results  - DMN and rECN were predominantly overconnected with other brain regions whereas SN and lECN was underconnected.

UnderConnectivityName: L Middle temporal gyrus extending to temporal pole
OverConnectivityName: L Posterior insula extending to posterior thalamus

Title: Alaerts, K., Nayar, K., Kelly, C., Raithel, J., Milham, M. P., & Di Martino, A. (2015). Age-related changes in intrinsic function of the superior temporal sulcus in autism spectrum disorders. Social cognitive and affective neuroscience, 10(10), 1413-1423.
Notes: In the secondary analysis they did scrubbing to see how the results change
Summary: Alaerts et al. investigated the resting state functional connectivity of posterior temporal sulcus (pSTS) which is a key region involved in social-cognitive processes. The goal was to investigate the impact of diagnosis on age related changes in pSTS FC connectivity with the whole brain. While exploring the intrinsic FC of pSTS in ASD vs TD regardless of age they observed underconnectivity of pSTS with fusiform gyrus, inferior parietal cortex, premotor cortex, insula and superior temporal gyrus.

UnderConnectivityName: Right Rolandic Operculum/ Inferior Parietal Cortex
Left Rolandic Operculum/ Inferior Parietal Cortex

Title: Cheng, W., Rolls, E. T., Gu, H., Zhang, J., & Feng, J. (2015). Autism: reduced connectivity between cortical areas involved in face expression, theory of mind, and the sense of self. Brain, 138(5), 1382-1393.
Notes: The ROI x ROI correlation is donebut not with all the voxels in the ROI.Only the significant voxels were taken.To see how these significant voxels were selected please read the paper. used the mean framewise displacement as a covariate when comparing the two groups during statistical analysis. No table was given demonstrating group differences. I created a table using the theory given in the 'Altered functional connectivity pattern' section. The MNI coordinates were taken from Table 1.
Summary: Cheng et al. utilized a novel all voxel pair connectivity approach to find out the voxels that had significantly altered functional connectivity in autistic individuals. After mapping the voxels to AAL atlas they found the significant ROIs that can be used in ROI x ROI functional connectivity analysis. The mean representative time series for each of the ROIs were thr mean of the significant voxel time series that lay in that ROI. They created ROI x ROI FC maps for each of the subjects  and then foud between group differences between ASD and TD. They observed both hyper or hypo connected in autistic individuals.
IQ Notes: Subjects were excluded if they had a full IQ exceeding 2 standard deviations

Title: Doyle-thomas, K. A. R., Lee, W., Foster, N. E. V, Tryfon, A., Ouimet, T., Hyde, K. L., … Anagnostou, E. (2015). Atypical Functional Brain Connectivity during Rest in Autism Spectrum Disorders. https://doi.org/10.1002/ana.24391
Scanner:
3T MR device (Tim Trio, VB17; Siemens, Erlangen,
Germany)
Summary:
Doyle Thomas et al. studied default mode brain network in adolescents and children using seed based functional connectivity. They used the left and right posterior cingulate cortex as seeds. The representational time course which was the mean of all the voxel time series of the eroded seed regions was correlated with al the voxels of the brain. 
They observed both over and under connectivity of both left and right PCC seed with multiple region of the brain in autistic subjects as compared to typically developing.

Title: Chien, H. Y., Lin, H. Y., Lai, M. C., Gau, S. S. F., & Tseng, W. Y. I. (2015). Hyperconnectivity of the Right Posterior Temporo‐parietal Junction Predicts Social Difficulties in Boys with Autism Spectrum Disorder. Autism Research, 8(4), 427-441.
Notes: First 5 volumes were discarded,With GSR the results were same, overconnectivity between same regions
Summary: pRTPJ is know to be involved in mentalizing and 'theory of mind'. Chien et al investigated the involvement of this region in the etiology of ASD. They hypothesised the alteration of FC in pRTPJ in aautistic individuals. They went ahead and analyzed pRTPJ using seed based approach and create FC map with alll the voxels of the brain. Between groupanalysis showed overconnectivity of pRTPJ with right ventral occipita-temporal cortex. No underconnectivity was reported.

Title: Jung, M., Kosaka, H., Saito, D. N., Ishitobi, M., Morita, T., Inohara, K., ... & Wada, Y. (2014). Default mode network in young male adults with autism spectrum disorder: relationship with autism spectrum traits. Molecular autism, 5(1), 35.
Notes: (FIQ) scores >85.
Scanner: 3-T imager (Discovery MR 750; General Electric Med- ical Systems, Milwaukee, WI, USA) and
Summary: In the quest for finding biomarkers that characterize ASD subjects have led many researchers analyze the Default Mode network. Jung t al. analyzed the intrinsic functional connectivity of two core regions of DMN - aMPFC and PCC. The FC analysis  was seed-voxel based and was done with the whole brain. Between group level analysis resulted in underconnectivity of aMPFC with paracentral lobule and middle frontal gyrus; and of PCC with medial prefrontal cortex.

Title: Fishman, I., Keown, C. L., Lincoln, A. J., Pineda, J. A., & Müller, R. A. (2014). Atypical cross talk between mentalizing and mirror neuron networks in autism spectrum disorder. JAMA psychiatry, 71(7), 751-760.
Notes: History of autism-related medical conditions (eg, epilepsy, Fragile X syndrome, tuberous sclerosis) served as an exclu- sionary criterion. But they had ADHD, depression, OCD etc. 5 volumes were discarded. Talaraich coordinates were converted to MNI. There is an error in the talaraich coordinates of left anterior intraparietal sulcus in Table 2. The z is 45 not 4.
Summary: Fishman et al. investigated 2 brain networks. One involved in 'Theory of mind (TOM)' and other the Mirror Neuron system(MNS) both of which are said to be involved in social processing which is impaired in ASD individuals. 4 TOM seeds and 6 MNS seeds were determined  by meta analysis. Seed to whole brain voxelwise FC was calculated. Between group difference for each seed revealed no significant differences in MNS seeds but reveled both over and underconnectivity with TOM seeds.

Title: Verly, M., Verhoeven, J., Zink, I., Mantini, D., Peeters, R., Deprez, S., ... & Lagae, L. (2014). Altered functional connectivity of the language network in ASD: role of classical language areas and cerebellum. NeuroImage: Clinical, 4, 374-382.
Notes: FIQ > 80
Summary: Verly et al. investigated the functional connectivity of language network in language impaired ASD subejcts. They determined the ROIs using activations in verb generation task. This resulted in 8 ROIs. They first created an ROI x ROI FC map for each subject and performed between group analysis on these. This was followed by seed based whole brain voxel-wise analysis using 2 seeds - Left IFG i.e. Brocas area and right cerebellar cortex. ROI xROI as well as seed based analysis resulted in underconnectivity in ASD subjects.

UnderConnectivityName: Left inferior parietal lobule, supramarginal gyrus
Left superior frontal gyrus, sup orb
Left middle frontal gyrus, premotor, SMA
Right middle frontal gyrus, premotor, SMA

Title: Eilam-Stock, T., Xu, P., Cao, M., Gu, X., Van Dam, N. T., Anagnostou, E., ... & He, Y. (2014). Abnormal autonomic and associated brain activities during rest in autism spectrum disorder. Brain, 137(1), 153-171.
Notes: Combined PCC L and R seeds ROI was not given. Individual L and R was taken from AAL atlas. For the combined MNI coordinated I used Harvard Oxford cortical atlas
Comorbidities: Exclusion criteria included epilepsy, history of schizophrenia, schizoaffective disorder or other Axis I mental disorders, except for obsessive-compulsive disorder (given the phenotypic overlap with ASD)
Summary: Eilam-Stock et al. analyzed the autonomic processing in ASD by measuring non-specific skin conductance response and investigated its relation ship with the intrinsic brain activity. They tested the effects of SCR on DMN connectivity (realized by taking 2 seeds - PCC, vMPFC) with the whole brain. In addition to these 2 seeds another seed in Insula was taken because of its putative involvement in autonomic and emotional processes in brain. Functional connectivity with the above 3 seeds revealed both over and under conenctivity in ASD individuals. Moreover the SCR was observed to contribute less to DMN connectivity in ASD individuals.

Title: Padmanabhan, A., Lynn, A., Foran, W., Luna, B., & O'Hearn, K. (2013). Age related changes in striatal resting state functional connectivity in autism. Frontiers in human neuroscience
SeedName: R inferior ventral striatum (Center of mass)
UnderConnectivityName: Left anterior cingulate cortex (Center of mass)
Notes: Instead of peak t value coordinates, centre of mass coordinates were given in MNI space. Non brain tissue (NBT) was also regressed out.
Summary: Padmanabhan et al analyzed the resting state FC of Striatum which is said to be involved in cognitive and affective funcions. They identified 6 bilateral seed regions in striatum from previous literature. First principle component was extracted from each of the seeds and correlated with all the voxels of the brain to construct a FC map. Between group analysis after controlling for age shows overconnectivity with parietal and underconnectivity with prefrontal cortex in ASD individuals as compared to typically developing.

SeedName: R dorsal caudal Putamen (Center of mass)
UnderConnectivityName: Left middle frontal gyrus (Center of mass)

SeedName: L dorsal caudal Putamen (Center of mass)

UnderConnectivityName: Left superior medial gyrus (Center of mass)

UnderConnectivityName: Left superior frontal gyrus (Center of mass)
OverConnectivityName: Left inferior parietal lobule (Center of mass)

SeedName: L dorsal rostral Putamen (Center of mass)
UnderConnectivityName: Left inferior frontal gyrus  (Center of mass)

SeedName: R ventral rostral Putamen (Center of mass)
UnderConnectivityName: Right inferior frontal gyrus (Center of mass)

Title: Delmonte, S., Gallagher, L., O’Hanlon, E., McGrath, J., & Balsters, J. H. (2013). Functional and structural connectivity of frontostriatal circuitry in Autism Spectrum Disorder. Frontiers in Human Neuroscience, 7, 430. https://doi.org/10.3389/fnhum.2013.00430
Notes: FIQ > 70, The principle eigenvariate of the BOLD time-courses of WM, CSF were used in CONN toolbox. They controlled for age, IQ and frame-wise displacements. Setting FWD as covariate is simar to scrubbing (cited to some other paper).  MNI coordinates were not explicitely given but was mentioned that the ROIs were taken fron Harvard Oxford Cortical/subcortical Atlas. Therefore I determined the coordinates from the atlas.
Comorbidities:
None, Four subjects in the ASD group had a secondary diagnosis of Attention Deficit Disorder
(ADD) or ADHD
Summary: Delmonte et al. investigated the fronto-striatal circuitry which is known to be involved in social interaction and communication. They did a multimodal analysis involving rs-fMRI as well as DTI.  ROIs were determined individually for frontal cortex (called source ROIs) and striatum(Target ROIs). ROI x ROI FC map for each subject was created between source and target ROI pairs which was then subjected  to between group comparisons. This resulted in purely overconnectivity between Source and Target ROIs in ASD individuals as compared to TD. The studied showed no structural connectivity but showed increased functional connectivity in fronto-striatal circuitary in ASD.

Title: Lynch, C. J., Uddin, L. Q., Supekar, K., Khouzam, A., Phillips, J., & Menon, V. (2013). Default mode network in childhood autism: posteromedial cortex heterogeneity and relationship with social deficits. Biological psychiatry, 74(3), 212-219.
Notes: This paper using a linear model predicts the social scores using connectivity measure. Also did the preprocessing without GSR but with WM  and CSF regression, Included the results in Supplementary but without coordinates of altered connectivity. FIQ > 70
Summary: Lynch et al investigated the DMN by taking 3 seeds in PCC, precuneus and Retrosplenial cortex. FC was calculated for each seed by correlating the seed time series with all the voxels of the brain. Between group analysis showed overconnectivity of PCC and RSC with multiple brain regions but Precuneus was observed to be underconnected in ASD individuals.

Title: von dem Hagen, E. A., Stoyanova, R. S., Baron-Cohen, S., & Calder, A. J. (2012). Reduced functional connectivity within and between ‘social’resting state networks in autism spectrum conditions. Social cognitive and affective neuroscience, 8(6), 694-701.

Title: Di Martino, A., Kelly, C., Grzadzinski, R., Zuo, X. N., Mennes, M., Mairena, M. A., ... & Milham, M. P. (2011). Aberrant striatal functional connectivity in children with autism. Biological psychiatry, 69(9), 847-856.
Notes: FIQ > 79
Summary: Martino et al investigated a subcortical brain structure - striatum. They used 3 claudate and 3 putamen seeds of each hemisphere and did seed to whole brain voxels FC analysis to create FC maps for each seed per subject. Between group analysis revealed hyperconnectivity of  multiple claudal seeds as well as multiple putamen seeds. One putamen seed was also observed to be underconnected in ASD.

Title: Weng, S. J., Wiggins, J. L., Peltier, S. J., Carrasco, M., Risi, S., Lord, C., & Monk, C. S. (2010). Alterations of resting state functional connectivity in the default network in adolescents with autism spectrum disorders. Brain research, 1313, 202-214.
Notes: IQ > 85
Summary: Weng et al. analyzed the DMN of individuals suffering form ASD and compared it with controls. They analyzed the functional connectivity of PCC seed with the whole brain but focussed their analysis on DMN regions.   They observed 9 out of 11 DMN regions to be under connected with PCC in ASD subjects.

Title: Monk, C. S., Peltier, S. J., Wiggins, J. L., Weng, S. J., Carrasco, M., Risi, S., & Lord, C. (2009). Abnormalities of intrinsic functional connectivity in autism spectrum disorders. Neuroimage, 47(2), 764-772.
Notes: When the subjects on meditation were not taken into account while group differences, the results were still same. Confused in whether PCC seed was correlated with all the voxels or just the other DMN regions. Coz the p value threshold was defined by 0.5 / 11 where 11 was the number of DMN regions. The timecourse of the seed was unit normalized to remove differences in variance between subjects.
Summary: Monk et al. analyzed the DMN by taking PCC as seed which is considered to be a core area of DMN. Seed-voxels based FC maps were creates using PCC as seed. Between group differences  were found. ASD showed under connectivity between PCC and the right superior frontal gyrus. They also showed over connectivity between PCC and some parts of Temporal lobe as well as right parahippocampul gyrus.

Title: Traynor, J. M., Doyle-Thomas, K. A. R., Hanford, L. C., Foster, N. E., Tryfon, A., Hyde, K. L., ... & Hall, G. B. C. (2018). Indices of repetitive behaviour are correlated with patterns of intrinsic functional connectivity in youth with autism spectrum disorder. Brain research, 1685, 79-90.
Summary: Traynor et al. analyzed the thalamocortical and cortico-basal ganglia  ROIs for its effects on repetitive behaviours. They did a seed based as well as ROI x ROI based analysis. They concluded their analysis by showing a predominant  over connectivity of basal gangalian regions -PCC, Putamen, and globus pallidus seeds with cortical sensory processing areas and thalamus with somatosensory and motor cortices. They also observed underconnectivity of Angular gyrus with superior temporal cortical area.

Title: Alaerts, K., Swinnen, S. P., & Wenderoth, N. (2016). Sex differences in autism: a resting-state fMRI investigation of functional brain connectivity in males and females. Social cognitive and affective neuroscience, 11(6), 1002-1016.
Notes: (site, mean FD, Full-scale IQ and age) used as covariates
Summary: As the autism prevalence in females is very low as compared to males, Alaerts et al. explored the functional brain connectivity differences in ASD males and females. In their analysis they did a seed to voxel whole brain analysis with Left and Right STS and PCC as well as ROI x ROI analysis with 200 ROis. Upon independent analysis of 2 groups - Males and females, they observed predominant underconnectivity in ASD males as compared to TD males  whereas over connectivity in female ASD subjects as compared to TD females.
